<rfc docName="draft-gravit-vcp-00" submissionType="IETF" category="info" ipr="trust200902" version="3" xml:lang="en">
  <front>
    <title abbrev="VCP">Verifiable Convergence Protocol (VCP) v0.1</title>
    <seriesInfo name="Internet-Draft" value="draft-gravit-vcp-00"/>
    <author fullname="Dr. Alex Konviser">
      <organization>Gravit Open Network Foundation</organization>
      <address>
        <postal><city>Zürich</city><country>Switzerland</country></postal>
        <email>ietf@gravit.space</email>
      </address>
    </author>
    <date year="2026" month="July" day="20"/>
    <area>sec</area>
    <workgroup>SCITT</workgroup>
    <keyword>VCP</keyword>
    <keyword>GQRVP</keyword>
    <abstract>
      <t>Verifiable Convergence Protocol (VCP) defines minimal data types and APIs for autonomous agents and human-machine systems to achieve epistemic convergence without centralized truth arbiters. VCP is transport-agnostic, blockchain-agnostic, and model-agnostic. Any system implementing VCP is an Epistemic Execution System (EES).</t>
      <t>The key invariant: C(manipulation) &gt; C(validation) for all Claim objects.</t>
    </abstract>
  </front>
  <middle>
    <section anchor="introduction">
      <name>Introduction</name>
      <t>As artificial intelligence transitions to autonomous agents capable of independent actions, the lack of a standardized mechanism for verifiable trust and epistemic convergence has become a critical bottleneck. VCP addresses this by providing a minimal protocol for claims, actions, and verifiable traces.</t>
      <t>The key invariant is that the cost of manipulating a Claim's confidence exceeds the cost of validating it: C(manipulation) &gt; C(validation).</t>
    </section>
    <section anchor="conformance">
      <name>Conformance</name>
      <t>A system is VCP-Compatible iff:</t>
      <ol>
        <li><t>It implements the 4 Core Endpoints in Section 4.</t></li>
        <li><t>Confidence for all Claims is computed via Multiplicative Weights Update plus Gossip Consensus as defined in Section 5 (GQRVP).</t></li>
        <li><t>All Action objects reference Claim as basis. Actions without basis MUST be rejected at Gateway.</t></li>
        <li><t>Trace is immutable, content-addressed, and publicly auditable.</t></li>
      </ol>
    </section>
    <section anchor="core-types">
      <name>Core Types</name>
      <section anchor="claim">
        <name>Claim</name>
        <t>The atomic unit of verifiable information.</t>
        <t><sourcecode type="json"><![CDATA[{
  "claim_id": "sha256:...",
  "content": "string",
  "provenance": [{"type": "url", "src": "string", "signed_by": "did:..."}],
  "confidence": "float 0.0-1.0",
  "created_at": "RFC3339",
  "trace": ["claim_id"]
}]]></sourcecode></t>
      </section>
      <section anchor="completeness">
        <name>Formal Completeness Boundary</name>
        <t>Formal-to-epistemic transition threshold: theta_critical = 0.731. When confidence is greater than or equal to threshold, system may treat result as formally sufficient. When below, SHOULD escalate to Continuum-style semantic verification.</t>
        <t>Empirical sybil-10x-g1.5 trace: 30 scores extracted, 0 below, 30 above threshold. Consistent with Godel-grounded design.</t>
      </section>
      <section anchor="attestation">
        <name>Attestation</name>
        <t>Cryptographic signature over a Claim by a DID.</t>
        <t><sourcecode type="json"><![CDATA[{
  "attestation_id": "sha256:...",
  "claim_id": "sha256:...",
  "issuer": "did:...",
  "signature": "bytes"
}]]></sourcecode></t>
      </section>
      <section anchor="action">
        <name>Action</name>
        <t>A proposed state change grounded in Claims.</t>
        <t><sourcecode type="json"><![CDATA[{
  "action_id": "sha256:...",
  "name": "string",
  "basis": ["claim_id"],
  "stake": "uint",
  "proposed_by": "did:..."
}]]></sourcecode></t>
      </section>
      <section anchor="trace">
        <name>Trace</name>
        <t>Immutable record of verification.</t>
        <t><sourcecode type="json"><![CDATA[{
  "trace_id": "sha256:...",
  "action_id": "sha256:...",
  "result": "ACCEPTED",
  "final_confidence": "float",
  "merkle_root": "bytes"
}]]></sourcecode></t>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section anchor="endpoints">
      <name>Core Endpoints</name>
      <t>All endpoints MUST be served over HTTPS. Bodies are application/json.</t>
      <section anchor="post-claim"><name>POST /v1/claim</name><t>Submit new Claim. Request: Claim without claim_id. Response 201: claim_id. 400: Invalid schema.</t></section>
      <section anchor="get-claim"><name>GET /v1/claim/{claim_id}</name><t>Retrieve Claim and current confidence. Response 200: claim, confidence, attestations, merkle_proof. 404: Not found.</t></section>
      <section anchor="post-verify"><name>POST /v1/action/verify</name><t>Verify Action. Request: Action. Response 200: status ACCEPTED or REJECTED, trace_id, reason. Gateway MUST reject if basis empty or confidence less than 0.731.</t></section>
      <section anchor="get-trace"><name>GET /v1/trace/{trace_id}</name><t>Retrieve immutable history. 200: Trace. 404: Not found.</t></section>
    </section>
    <section anchor="gqrvp">
      <name>GQRVP Security Parameters</name>
      <t>To prevent Sybil and amplification attacks, VCP-Compatible implementations MUST use eta=0.2, gamma=1.5, eps=0.1. Formal proof of 67 percent Byzantine resilience under these parameters is given in /specs/RFC/GQRVP-security.md.</t>
    </section>
    <section anchor="iana">
      <name>IANA Considerations</name>
      <t>This document has no IANA actions.</t>
    </section>
    <section anchor="security">
      <name>Security Considerations</name>
      <t>VCP does not resolve conflicts caused by asymmetry of goals. VCP guarantees that cost of manipulating confidence exceeds cost of validating it, given honest supermajority of stake-weighted attention.</t>
    </section>
  </middle>
